\subsection{Normalising the Canvas hostname}

Users naturally think in hostnames like [[canvas.kth.se]], but the
[[canvasapi]] client needs a full base URL.
We centralise this normalization so that the CLI and package API cannot drift.

<<functions>>=
def normalize_hostname(hostname):
  """Return ``hostname`` as a URL suitable for ``canvasapi.Canvas``."""
  if "://" not in hostname:
    hostname = f"https://{hostname}"
  return hostname
@


\subsection{Configuring retry policy with exponential backoff}

The shared loader is also the right place to configure retry behaviour.
Without this, the command-line client and the package API could end up with
different resilience characteristics even though they talk to the same Canvas
server.

The retry policy itself stays unchanged.
We still retry transient failures such as [[429]], [[500]], [[502]], [[503]],
and [[504]] using exponential backoff with jitter.
The only difference is where that policy lives: in the shared loader rather
than in the CLI bootstrap.

<<functions>>=
def configure_canvas_retry_policy(canvas):
  """Install the shared retry policy on a Canvas session."""
  retry_strategy = Retry(
    total=10,
    backoff_factor=2,
    backoff_max=256,
    backoff_jitter=0.3,
    status_forcelist=[429, 500, 502, 503, 504],
    allowed_methods=["HEAD", "GET", "PUT", "DELETE", "OPTIONS", "TRACE", "POST"],
    respect_retry_after_header=True,
  )

  adapter = HTTPAdapter(max_retries=retry_strategy)
  canvas._Canvas__requester._session.mount("https://", adapter)
  canvas._Canvas__requester._session.mount("http://", adapter)
  return canvas
@

When no encrypted cache is available, we create a fresh [[Canvas]] instance and
immediately configure it with the shared retry policy.

This contrasts the cache-hit and cache-miss paths deliberately.
Cached clients arrive with their warmed state already attached, while cache
misses must construct a fresh client and then receive the same retry behaviour
so that callers do not observe different network resilience depending on where
the object came from.

<<functions>>=
def create_canvas(hostname, token):
  """Create a new ``Canvas`` instance with shared retry configuration."""
  canvas = Canvas(hostname, token)
  return configure_canvas_retry_policy(canvas)
@


\subsection{Loading a configured Canvas client}

This is the public entry point shared by the CLI and the top-level package.
It hides three small decisions that should stay coupled:
\begin{enumerate}
\item where to read credentials from,
\item whether to reuse the encrypted object cache,
\item how to construct a fresh client when the cache misses.
\end{enumerate}

Keeping these decisions together prevents the command-line interface and the
package API from drifting apart.
If each caller reimplemented the sequence independently, they could easily end
up disagreeing about cache semantics, retry configuration, or how missing
credentials should fail.

The function returns the [[canvas]] object together with the normalized
[[hostname]] and [[token]].
Those values are needed later when the caller wants to save the encrypted cache
again.

<<functions>>=
def load_configured_canvas(config, use_cache=True):
  """Return configured Canvas object and cache metadata.

  The return value is the triple ``(canvas, hostname, token)``.
  """
  import canvaslms.cli.login

  hostname, token = canvaslms.cli.login.load_credentials(config)

  if not (hostname and token):
    raise CanvasCredentialsError("No hostname or token, run `canvaslms login`")

  hostname = normalize_hostname(hostname)

  if use_cache:
    canvas = load_canvas_cache(token, hostname)
    if canvas:
      return canvas, hostname, token

  return create_canvas(hostname, token), hostname, token
@

